<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-784-998  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 784 998.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  August 20 1990 v36 n1823 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ALR: 386SX lag to hobble sales rise. (Advanced Logic ResearchInc.'s inventory of 80386SX microprocessors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Deagon, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Advanced Logic Research Inc (ALR) expects its inventory of 386SXmicroprocessors to return to normal by Dec 1990, but revenuegrowth will be kept at 'modest' levels through Nov 1990 by recentshortages of the chip.andP;  The company's aggressive approach toproduct sales was slowed by a lack of 386SX chips.andP;  The shortagewas also blamed for ALR's decline in revenues in its 3rd qtr to$37.5 million from $44.8 million in the 2nd qtr.andP;  ALR has used itssupply of 386SX chips from Intel faster than expected in partbecause of its aggressive market promotions.andP;  The firm gave awayfree 386SX upgrades to buyers of its low-end 286-based systems inMar 1990 and offered upgrades for only $99 in Apr 1990.andP;  ALRreports that its revenues increased 159 percent to $121.8 millionin the most recent nine-month period from $47.1 million in thenine-month period ending a year ago.andP;  Earnings increased 300percent in the period to $8.8 million from $2.2 million a yearearlier.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Advanced Logic Research Inc. (finance).andO;Product:   Intel 80386SX (Microprocessor) (supply and demand).andO;Topic:     ManufacturersSupplyRevenueProfitThird QuarterMicroprocessorsMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>